"""
MKT Context Commentary — Psalms chapters 9–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-9-17.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/psalms.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/psalms.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/ellicott/psalms.json (philological background)
- data/commentary/jfb/psalms.json (historical context)

Key decisions in this range:
- Psalms 9–10 treated as a single acrostic poem split by LXX tradition; noted at Ps 9:1
- Muth-labben (Ps 9 superscription): uncertain musical/cultic direction; not over-interpreted
- Miktam (Ps 16): genre term left as technical note; NT use of Ps 16:10 noted at that verse
- 'Holy ones in the land' (Ps 16:3): read as the pious covenant community
- nābāl in Ps 14:1: practical atheism (denial of divine governance), not speculative atheism
- Entrance liturgy framework applied to Ps 15 (parallel: Ps 24, Isa 33:14-16, Mic 6:6-8)
- 'Apple of your eye' (Ps 17:8): etymological note on îšôn ('little man') included
- Ps 14:3 noted as the text Paul quotes in Rom 3:10-12 for universal human sinfulness
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PSALMS = {
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>Psalms 9 and 10 form a single acrostic poem in Hebrew — successive stanzas begin with successive letters of the alphabet (<em>aleph</em> through <em>taw</em>). The LXX split them into two psalms and most Western translations follow that division, but the Hebrew Psalter (MT) treats them as one. The acrostic form is a wisdom device: completing the alphabet signals total coverage of the subject from A to Z. The superscription <em>ʿal-mût labbēn</em> ("to Muth-labben") is obscure — likely a tune name or cultic performance direction; no consensus exists on its meaning.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The verbs of praise cluster in vv. 1-2: give thanks, declare, rejoice, be glad, sing. This rhetorical multiplication of praise-terms is characteristic of the Psalter\'s hymnic register and signals a formal song of thanksgiving following a military or national deliverance. "O Most High" (<em>ʿElyôn</em>) is a divine epithet shared with Canaanite religion (El Elyon, attested at Ugarit) that Israel claimed for YHWH alone — it emphasizes sovereignty over all peoples, not only Israel.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The turning back of enemies "before your face" (<em>millĕpānêkā</em>) signals divine presence driving them out — the same language used of Israel\'s conquest in Deuteronomy (1:30; 9:3). In ANE victory accounts, the flight of enemies at the divine presence was the standard evidence of divine warfare. The stumbling and perishing of enemies frames the following section on divine judgment over the nations.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"You sat on the throne, judging with righteousness" — the image of God enthroned as judge corresponds to the divine council imagery of the ANE, where the high god presides over lesser deities and adjudicates human disputes. In Israelite theology, YHWH alone occupies this throne (cf. Ps 82). The psalmist\'s personal vindication ("my right and my cause") merges with cosmic divine justice — the individual\'s case is heard by the judge of all the earth.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The nations (<em>gôyim</em>) are the standard foil in Davidic psalms — the enemies of Israel\'s king are also enemies of YHWH\'s order. "Blotting out their name forever" echoes the destruction of Amalek (Exod 17:14; Deut 25:19) and uses the ANE idiom for total eradication: to destroy a name is to destroy memory, lineage, and legacy. Name-survival was the ancient equivalent of ongoing existence in the community\'s collective memory.</p>',
    "6": '<p>This verse shifts to direct address of the enemy. "Perpetual ruin" (<em>šōʾôt leneṣaḥ</em>) — <em>šōʾāh</em> is the same root used in post-biblical Hebrew for the Holocaust (Shoah), meaning desolation, ruin. The uprooting of cities evokes conquest imagery. "Their memory has perished" repeats the name-blotting theme of v. 5: in ANE culture, one\'s legacy resided in name and descendants, so erasure of memory was the ultimate defeat.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"But the LORD sits enthroned forever" — the contrast with v. 6 (enemy\'s end vs. God\'s eternal throne) is the theological hinge of the poem. <em>Yāšab lĕʿôlām</em> echoes the enthronement psalms (Pss 29, 47, 93, 96-99) in which YHWH\'s eternal kingship is proclaimed. In Second Temple worship this throne language functioned as a counter-claim against the pretensions of successive empires (Assyrian, Babylonian, Persian, Greek).</p>',
    "8": '<p>Universal judgment: "He judges the world (<em>tēbēl</em>) with righteousness; he rules the peoples with equity (<em>mêšārîm</em>)." <em>Tēbēl</em> is the inhabited world — all nations, not only Israel. <em>Mêšārîm</em> (equity, uprightness) is the opposite of judicial corruption. In the ANE world where gods were tribal and their justice parochial, the claim that Israel\'s God is the impartial judge of all peoples was a radical theological claim.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"The LORD is a refuge for the oppressed (<em>dak</em>), a stronghold in times of trouble." <em>Dak</em> means crushed, ground down — one broken by circumstances or oppressors. This verse is a thesis statement for the entire Pss 9-10 meditation. The image of YHWH as stronghold (<em>miśgāb</em> — high tower, inaccessible height) is the standard metaphor for royal protection of the vulnerable in both biblical and ANE tradition: the king builds strongholds in which the weak can shelter.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Those who know your name will trust in you" — in Hebrew, "knowing the name" is not mere cognitive familiarity but covenantal experience of the person. YHWH\'s name carries the history of his faithfulness (Exod 3:14-15; 34:5-7). "You have never abandoned those who seek you" grounds the call to trust in historical testimony. <em>Dāraš</em> (seek) is the standard word for earnest inquiry directed at God — the same root as seeking God\'s face in the sanctuary (Ps 27:8).</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Sing praises to the LORD who dwells in Zion; declare his deeds among the nations" — Zion as the center of universal proclamation is central to the Zion theology developed in Isaiah and Micah (Isa 2:2-4; Mic 4:1-4). Second Temple Judaism viewed Zion as the point from which YHWH\'s Torah and justice would radiate outward to all peoples. The call to "declare his deeds among the nations" anticipates the missionary dimension developed more fully in Isaiah\'s Servant Songs.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"The one who avenges bloodshed (<em>dāmîm</em>)" — blood-vengeance was a defined social institution in ancient Israel. The <em>gōʾēl haddām</em> (avenger of blood) was a kinsman obligated to pursue the killer of a family member (Num 35; Deut 19). The psalmist applies this kin-redeemer role to God himself: YHWH is the ultimate avenger who does not forget the cry of the <em>ʿănāwîm</em> (humble, poor). The humble in the Psalter are those without a human advocate who therefore rely entirely on divine advocacy.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Be gracious to me" (<em>ḥānnēnî</em>) — the standard petition formula in lament psalms. The shift from praise (vv. 1-12) to personal petition (v. 13) is characteristic of the Psalms\' movement from the general to the particular, from God\'s cosmic victories to one\'s own suffering. "You who lift me back from the gates of death" — the gates of Sheol were a concrete spatial image; to be near death was to be at the threshold of the underworld domain (cf. Isa 38:10; Job 38:17).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"The gates of daughter Zion" — <em>bat-ṣiyyôn</em> (daughter Zion) is a personification of Jerusalem as a young woman, a figure appearing frequently in the Prophets (Isa 1:8; 16:1; Mic 4:8; Lam 1:6). Gates in ancient cities were the civic center — where courts convened, commerce happened, and public announcements were made (Ruth 4:1-11; Prov 31:23; Amos 5:12, 15). To declare praises "in the gates" is to make the proclamation as public and official as possible.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"The nations have sunk in the pit they made" — the retributive justice motif: the trap set for the righteous catches the wicked themselves (cf. Ps 7:15-16; Prov 26:27; Eccl 10:8). This boomerang pattern is a major wisdom theme in the Psalter and in Proverbs. The "concealed net" (<em>rešet tāmĕnû</em>) likely refers to the literal hunting trap — a net staked in the ground and covered with leaves to catch animals, used metaphorically for hidden schemes.</p>',
    "16": '<p><em>Higgaion Selah</em> — two enigmatic liturgical terms. <em>Higgaion</em> (related to <em>hāgāh</em>, to murmur/meditate) possibly indicates a meditative interlude or a specific musical instruction. <em>Selah</em> appears 71 times in the Psalter and 3 times in Habakkuk — likely a liturgical pause for reflection or a musical rest, though its exact function is debated. "Ensnared by the work of their own hands" repeats the retributive pattern of v. 15 with the additional irony of self-entrapment.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"The wicked will return to Sheol (<em>šĕʾôl</em>), all the nations that forget God." Sheol in the Hebrew Bible is the realm of the dead — not a place of punishment in the later developed sense but the underworld destination of all who die, the land of shadows and silence (Job 10:21-22; Isa 14:9-11). The claim here is that those who "forget God" — who live as if divine governance does not exist — will return to that realm. The verb <em>yāšûbû</em> implies they originate there, a creation-ex-nihilo motif.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"The needy (<em>ʾebyôn</em>) will not always be forgotten" — the Psalter\'s vocabulary of poverty is nuanced: <em>ʾebyôn</em> (economically needy), <em>ʿānî</em> (oppressed, afflicted), <em>dallîm</em> (weak, lowly), <em>ʿănāwîm</em> (humble, meek). These categories overlap but carry distinct social implications. Second Temple covenant ethics placed particular responsibility on the community to protect these groups (Deut 15:11; Isa 58:6-7). The promise that hope will not "perish forever" directly counters the wicked\'s permanent ruin (v. 6).</p>',
    "19": '<p>"Rise up, O LORD! Let not man have his way; let the nations be judged in your presence!" — the imperative <em>qûmāh</em> (rise up) is a standard battle-cry petition (Num 10:35; Pss 3:7; 7:6; 10:12; 17:13). "Man" (<em>ʾĕnôš</em> — frail, mortal humanity) in contrast to God deflates imperial pretension; the same contrast appears in Isa 31:3 ("The Egyptians are human, not God"). To be judged "in your presence" (<em>ʿal-pānêkā</em>) is to stand before the divine court — exactly what the wicked have denied would happen (Ps 10:4, 11, 13).</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Strike them with fear, O LORD" (<em>šîtāh yhwh môrāh</em>) — <em>môrāh</em> is the terror induced by divine presence and action; not psychological fear but the overwhelming awe that accompanies theophany. The goal is recognition: "let the nations know they are only human" (<em>ʾĕnôš</em>). <em>Selah</em> closes the psalm (the first half of the 9-10 acrostic) with a liturgical pause, inviting the congregation to absorb the contrast between divine sovereignty and human frailty that the entire poem has established.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 10 continues the acrostic of Psalm 9 in the Hebrew Psalter — this is the second panel of the A-to-Z meditation on divine justice. The opening <em>lāmmāh</em> (why) is the classic challenge of the lament genre — a direct rhetorical confrontation with God\'s apparent absence. "Hide yourself in times of trouble (<em>ʿittôt bĕṣārāh</em>)" uses the idiom of God hiding his face (<em>hissatēr pānîm</em>), which in covenant theology signals withdrawal of favor or presence (Isa 8:17; 54:8; Ps 13:1; 27:9). This psalm is one of the most vivid portraits of social oppression in the Psalter.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"In his arrogance (<em>bĕgaʾăwat</em>) the wicked person persecutes the poor" — the predatory imagery escalates through the psalm: the wicked is described as a prowling hunter (vv. 8-10) and a crouching lion (v. 9). This social portrait matches realities well-documented in ancient Israel and Second Temple Judaism: wealthy landowners exploiting tenant farmers, creditors seizing collateral in violation of Torah protections (cf. Neh 5:1-5; Amos 8:4-6; Isa 5:8). The retribution petition — "let him be caught in the very schemes he has devised" — is the boomerang theme.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The wicked person boasts of the cravings of his heart (<em>taʾăwat napšô</em>)" — self-satisfaction in greed. "Curses and spurns the LORD" — the Hebrew uses the verb <em>bēraḵ</em> (bless) as a euphemism for "curse" (the same softening appears in Job 1:5, 11; 2:5, 9), a scribal device to avoid writing the blaspheming word directly. The contrast throughout the psalm is between the wicked\'s self-blessing and YHWH\'s blessing of the poor (Ps 9:18).</p>',
    "4": '<p>"In all his thinking, there is no place for God" — the classic statement of practical atheism. <em>ʾên ʾĕlōhîm kol-maḥšĕbôtāyw</em> (literally: all his thoughts — "no God"). This is not the philosophical atheism of the Enlightenment but the functional atheism of one who acts as if God does not govern human affairs. Second Temple wisdom literature (Ben Sira, Wisdom of Solomon) treats this as the root of all wickedness: the failure to account for divine judgment in one\'s practical decisions.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"His ways always succeed" — the theological scandal at the heart of this lament: the wicked prosper. This is the pressing question of Pss 37, 49, 73, and the book of Job. "Your judgments are too high for him to perceive" — not that divine judgments are intellectually incomprehensible, but that the wicked\'s diminished moral vision cannot see them. The wicked "sneers at all his enemies" — success breeds contempt for any opposition. The Psalter does not deny this experience; it holds the tension honestly.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"He says in his heart, \'I will never be shaken (<em>bal-ʾemmoṭ</em>); through all generations I will face no trouble.\'" The heart-speech of the wicked (vv. 6, 11, 13) is a rhetorical device to expose the interior logic of oppression. The phrase <em>bal-ʾemmoṭ</em> ("will not be shaken") deliberately inverts the security language the Psalter applies to the righteous (Ps 15:5; 16:8; 21:7; 62:2). The wicked has appropriated covenant-stability language for his own arrogance — a theological usurpation the psalmist exposes.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"His mouth is full of cursing, deceit, and fraud; under his tongue are trouble and wickedness" — the anatomy of wicked speech. In ANE thought, curse formulas carried real causal power; to be under a curse was a genuine social-spiritual threat. The under-the-tongue image is forensic: the tongue conceals what the mouth will eventually release. "Trouble (<em>ʿāmāl</em>) and wickedness (<em>ʾāwen</em>)" — ʾāwen is a key word in the Psalter\'s moral vocabulary, combining meanings of wickedness, idolatry, and emptiness.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"He lurks in ambush near the villages" — the rural social setting: isolated farmsteads and small communities were vulnerable to strongmen who operated outside the protection of urban courts. The "innocent" (<em>nāqî</em>) he kills are those without legal standing. Vv. 8-10 use predator-prey imagery (lion, net, snare) that was standard in Egyptian and Mesopotamian wisdom texts for describing the oppressor. The psalmist maps ANE hunting vocabulary onto social exploitation — making the oppressor\'s predatory nature visible.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"He crouches like a lion in his lair; he lies in wait to catch the poor" — the lion as predator is one of the Psalter\'s persistent metaphors (Pss 7:2; 17:12; 22:13; 57:4). In Israelite pastoral culture, lions preying on livestock were a real threat (1 Sam 17:34-37; Amos 3:12); the metaphor carries immediate visceral force for an agricultural audience. The poor (<em>ʿānî</em>) are structurally vulnerable: without land, family network, or access to courts — those who cannot defend themselves.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"He crouches and springs, and the helpless fall by his strength" — <em>dakkîm</em> (the crushed/helpless) echoes the <em>dak</em> of Ps 9:9. The abruptness of the verse (only 3 words in Hebrew: "he crouches, he springs, the weak fall") mimics the sudden violence of the predatory act. In the ancient economy, "falling by strength" could mean debt-bondage, seizure of property, or physical coercion — all forms of power available to the strong against those without social protection.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"God has forgotten; he has hidden his face; he will never notice" — the wicked\'s three-part denial mirrors vv. 4 and 6: a consistent alternative theology. "Hiding the face" (<em>hissatîr pānîm</em>) was a covenant idiom for divine withdrawal that the wicked here declares permanent. The theological scandal of divine silence in the face of oppression was not only a personal spiritual crisis but a communal challenge to the entire covenant framework in which YHWH protects the vulnerable.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Rise up, O LORD! O God, lift up your hand! Do not forget the afflicted!" — the imperative petitions (<em>qûmāh, nĕśāʾ yādĕkā</em>) directly counter the wicked\'s claim that God has forgotten. "Lift up your hand" is the gesture of power and striking — the raised hand prepares to act (cf. Exod 7:5; Deut 32:40). This petition echoes Ps 9:19 and reflects the liturgical context: the congregation physically enacting the prayer, perhaps with raised hands, prostration, or crying out.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Why does the wicked person despise God and say in his heart, \'You won\'t call me to account\'?" — <em>nāʾaṣ</em> (despise, treat with contempt) is a strong term for active repudiation. The wicked\'s inner speech "You won\'t call me to account" (<em>lōʾ tidrōš</em>) uses the verb <em>dāraš</em> (seek/require/demand): God will neither inquire into his actions nor demand accountability. This inverts the covenant: in which YHWH does seek and does require (Deut 18:19; Amos 5:4; Isa 55:6).</p>',
    "14": '<p>"But you do see! You observe trouble and grief and take it into your hands" — the rhetorical pivot. Against the wicked\'s assumption of divine indifference, the psalmist asserts divine attentiveness: God sees, observes, and intervenes. "The helpless person (<em>yātôm</em> — the fatherless/orphan) entrusts himself to you" — the orphan was among the most legally vulnerable in ancient Israelite society. To be fatherless was to lose one\'s <em>gōʾēl</em> (kinsman-redeemer), one\'s advocate before courts, and one\'s social standing.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Break the arm of the wicked and the evildoer" — "arm" (<em>zĕrôaʿ</em>) is the standard symbol of power and strength (cf. Ezek 30:21-22, where God explicitly breaks Pharaoh\'s arm). To break the arm is to permanently incapacitate the means of oppression. "Call his wickedness to account until there is none left" — the demand is not merely personal punishment but the exhaustion of the capacity for wickedness: complete moral accountability leading to complete moral incapacitation.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"The LORD is King for ever and ever; the nations will vanish from his land" — the divine kingship proclamation (<em>yhwh melek ʿôlām wāʿed</em>) closes the lament with the enthronement affirmation. "The nations will vanish from his land (<em>ʾarṣô</em>)" — the land belongs to YHWH as its true owner; those who occupy it without acknowledging him are transient tenants. In Second Temple theology this pointed both to Eretz Israel and, eschatologically, to the whole earth over which YHWH would rule.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"LORD, you have heard the desire (<em>taʾăwat</em>) of the humble" — this word (<em>taʾăwāh</em>) was used in v. 3 for the wicked\'s cravings. Now it reappears for the humble\'s longing — a deliberate contrast. The wicked\'s desires lead to exploitation; the humble\'s desire is for vindication and survival. "You will strengthen their heart" — in Hebrew thought the heart (<em>lēb</em>) is the seat of will, intention, and courage; to strengthen the heart is to resolve and empower the will for perseverance.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"To vindicate the fatherless and the oppressed, so that mortal man will no longer strike terror" — the psalm closes where it opened: the question of human power over the vulnerable. The final petition is cosmic in scope: that the whole pattern of oppression over the defenseless would end. "Mortal man" (<em>ʾĕnôš min-hāʾāreṣ</em> — man from the earth) reprises Ps 9:20\'s deflation of human arrogance. The Pss 9-10 acrostic closes with this eschatological hope: the human terror-imposer brought to nothing before the eternal King.</p>'
  },
  "11": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 11 is a psalm of trust in the face of counsel to flee. David\'s counselors or friends advise escape to the mountains — presumably because the danger is too acute to face. The "mountain" (<em>hārekem</em>) is probably the Judean highlands (not Zion), a refuge for fugitives in the David narratives (1 Sam 23-26). David\'s refusal — "In the LORD I take refuge" — is the psalm\'s theological claim: the divine protector supersedes any geographic strategy. The tension between the counselors\' pragmatic wisdom and the psalmist\'s covenantal trust is the pastoral core of the poem.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"The wicked string the bow; they have set their arrows on the string to shoot in the darkness (<em>ʾōpel</em>)" — the nocturnal archer was a real threat in the ancient world, but the image also captures hidden malice: the attack comes without warning, in darkness, targeting "the upright in heart (<em>yiśrê-lēb</em>)." Upright-hearted people are the ones who cannot be corrupted by the counselors\' pragmatic flight advice — their very integrity makes them targets. ANE military contexts regularly described ambush arrows as the weapon of treachery.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"If the foundations are destroyed, what can the righteous do?" — the counselors\' logic: if the basic structures of justice and social order have collapsed, individual righteousness has no purchase; flight is the only rational option. <em>Šātôt</em> (foundations) can mean the foundations of society, the covenant order, or the temple mount. Second Temple readers in the aftermath of the Babylonian destruction of 587 BCE would have heard this as directly relevant — what does covenant faithfulness mean when every institutional support of that covenant has been razed?</p>',
    "4": '<p>"The LORD is in his holy temple; the LORD\'s throne is in heaven" — the counter-claim to despair. Two levels: the earthly temple (where YHWH is present) and the heavenly throne (from which he governs). Both are secure and neither depends on the survival of human institutions. "His eyes observe; his eyelids examine (<em>yiḥĕzû, yiblĕnû</em>) humanity" — the examining gaze is forensic. <em>Bāḥan</em> (examine/test) is the metallurgist\'s assaying verb: God is scrutinizing humanity as a refiner tests metal. He is neither absent nor indifferent.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The LORD tests (<em>bōḥēn</em>) the righteous" — the divine testing of the righteous is a covenant theme: God tests to refine (Deut 8:2-3; Job 1-2; Ps 66:10; Zech 13:9). "His soul hates the wicked and the one who loves violence (<em>ḥāmās</em>)" — <em>ḥāmās</em> (violence, cruelty) is one of the most weighty moral terms in the Hebrew Bible. It is listed alongside corruption as the reason for the flood (Gen 6:11-13) and is the defining characteristic of the wicked throughout the Psalter. God\'s hatred of <em>ḥāmās</em> is not emotional pique but the covenantal rejection of the anti-creation force.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Let him rain down coals on the wicked; fire and sulfur and a scorching wind (<em>rûaḥ zilʿāpôt</em>)" — Sodom imagery (Gen 19:24) is deliberate: fire and sulfur raining from heaven is the paradigmatic divine judgment on the utterly wicked city. The scorching wind is likely the <em>sirocco</em> (east wind from the Arabian desert), which withers vegetation and exhausts humans. Fire from above, sulfur from below, scorching wind from the east — judgment from all directions simultaneously. "Their cup (<em>mĕnāt kôsām</em>)" — cup of wrath contrasts sharply with the cup of blessing in Ps 16:5.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"For the LORD is righteous (<em>ṣaddîq</em>); he loves righteous deeds (<em>ṣĕdāqôt</em>); the upright will see his face (<em>yĕḥĕzû pānāyw</em>)" — the closing affirmation. To "see God\'s face" was the goal of temple worship (Ps 17:15; 27:4; 63:2) — the culmination of access to the divine presence normally mediated through the sanctuary. The upright\'s access to the divine presence is grounded in the correspondence between their character and YHWH\'s own character: as he is righteous, the righteous see him. The psalm reverses the flight-counsel of v. 1: those who trust rather than flee are the ones who arrive at the divine presence.</p>'
  },
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 12\'s superscription mentions the "Sheminith" (<em>šĕmînît</em>) — possibly an eight-stringed instrument, a musical register (eighth = bass), or a liturgical category. The same direction appears in Ps 6. The psalm is a lament over total collapse of faithful speech in society. The hyperbole "the faithful have vanished from among humanity" is characteristic of the lament genre\'s extreme formulation (cf. Elijah\'s "I alone am left," 1 Kgs 19:10) — not a census claim but a rhetorical expression of moral isolation. The crisis of trustworthy speech was perennial in ancient courts and communities.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Everyone lies to his neighbor; they speak with flattering lips and a divided heart (<em>lēb wālēb</em>)" — <em>lēb wālēb</em> (heart and heart = divided heart) is the idiom for duplicity: one public heart, one hidden heart. To have two hearts violated the fundamental social bond of covenant community. In ancient Israelite ethics, integrity meant the alignment of speech and heart (cf. Ps 15:2 — "speaks truth from the heart"). <em>Šāwĕʾ</em> (falsehood, emptiness) is paired with smooth speech — the combination of empty words and manipulative delivery.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"May the LORD cut off all flattering lips" — the petition against <em>siptê ḥălāqôt</em> (smooth/flattering lips) and <em>lāšôn mĕdabberet gĕdōlôt</em> (tongue that speaks great things, boastfully). The contrast throughout the psalm is between two kinds of speech: human speech (manipulative, boastful, self-serving) and divine speech (pure, reliable — v. 6). In ANE thought, words carried power — false words damaged the social fabric by corrupting the medium through which the community sustained trust and covenant loyalty.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"With our words we will prevail; our lips are our own — who can lord it over us?" — the claim of autonomous speech: no accountability to God or community. In ancient culture, one\'s word was one\'s bond, and to renege on it was to damage one\'s social honor (<em>kābôd</em>). The arrogance here is cosmological: to claim autonomy of speech is to deny that language is given by and accountable to the Creator. "Who can lord it over us?" denies any transcendent authority — a posture the psalm regards as both morally and theologically self-deceptive.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"\'Because the poor are oppressed and the needy groan, I will now arise,\' says the LORD" — a direct divine oracle (<em>nĕʾum yhwh</em>) embedded within the lament, a technique more common in prophetic literature than the Psalms (cf. Isa 33:10 — "now I will arise"). The direct divine response to the poor\'s cry mirrors the Exodus pattern: God hears the groaning (<em>nĕʾāqāh</em>) of the oppressed and acts (Exod 2:24; 6:5). "I will set them in the safety for which they long (<em>yāpîaḥ lô</em>)" — the safety is precisely the covenantal protection the corrupt community has denied them.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"The words of the LORD are pure words, like silver refined in a furnace in the ground, purified seven times" — the great contrast. Human speech is corrupt (vv. 2-4); divine speech is maximally pure. The metallurgical image is precise: silver refined in a clay furnace (<em>ʿălîl lāʾāreṣ</em>), heated repeatedly to remove all dross. Seven is the number of completeness — sevenfold refining = absolute purity. This is the standard by which all other speech is measured. Second Temple Judaism applied this to Torah: God\'s word is perfectly reliable (cf. Ps 19:7-10).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"You, O LORD, will keep them; you will protect us from this generation (<em>haddôr hazzeh</em>) forever" — the pronouns shift ambiguously (them/us) but the meaning is clear: God preserves both his words and those who trust in them against the corrupt generation. "This generation" (<em>haddôr hazzeh</em>) is a recurring moral category in Scripture — not a biological cohort but a spiritually defined community characterized by faithlessness (cf. Deut 1:35; Ps 78:8; Matt 12:39). The righteous are embedded in history alongside the corrupt and require divine protection.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"The wicked parade on every side when what is vile is honored among humanity" — the closing observation rather than resolution. When the honor-system is corrupted — when the dishonorable gain honor — the wicked multiply unchecked. Honor and shame were the primary social regulators in ancient Mediterranean culture; when the system inverts (vileness honored rather than shamed), the mechanisms of social accountability collapse entirely. The psalm ends with this ongoing reality, having placed its hope entirely in the divine speech of vv. 5-7 rather than in social reform.</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 13 is the classic short lament — six verses moving from abandonment (vv. 1-2) through petition (vv. 3-4) to trust and praise (vv. 5-6). The fourfold "<em>ʿad-ʾānāh</em>" (how long) is one of the most repeated formulas of the lament genre (cf. Pss 74:10; 79:5; 89:46; Hab 1:2; Jer 12:4). It does not expect an answer; it is rhetorical pressure applied to God. "Will you forget me forever (<em>lĕneṣaḥ</em>)?" — <em>neṣaḥ</em> means both "forever" and "completely/permanently," compounding the feeling of absolute divine absence.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"How long must I wrestle with my thoughts (<em>ʾāśît ʿēṣôt bĕnapšî</em> — setting plans/counsels in my soul)?" — the psalmist is not passively suffering but is exhausting himself in deliberation, turning over options, none of them working. "My enemy (<em>ʾōybî</em>) triumphs over me" is the social dimension: the internal suffering has external visibility. In the honor-shame culture of the ancient world, the enemy watches and interprets the psalmist\'s distress as evidence that God has abandoned him — the individual\'s suffering is a public theological statement about YHWH\'s reliability.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Give light to my eyes" (<em>hāʾîrāh ʿênay</em>) — the standard petition for renewed vitality. In Hebrew medical thought, dimming eyes signal mortal weakness (1 Sam 14:27, 29 — Jonathan\'s eyes "lit up" when he ate honey; 1 Sam 3:2 — Eli\'s eyes had grown dim). "Lest I fall into the sleep of death" (<em>pen-ʾîšan hammāwet</em>) — to die was to fall asleep into Sheol (Dan 12:2; Jer 51:39). The sleep of death is not peaceful rest but permanent cessation; the petition is for the light of renewed life before the threshold is crossed.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Lest my enemy say, \'I have overcome him,\'" — the social stakes of the individual\'s survival. In an honor-shame culture, the psalmist\'s death would be read publicly as YHWH\'s defeat; the enemy would gloat (<em>yāgîl</em>). This is not vanity but covenantal argument: God has a stake in not being publicly shamed by the victory of those who oppose his covenant servant. The psalmist\'s appeal to God\'s honor as part of his petition is bold but conventional in the lament genre — "act for your name\'s sake" (cf. Ps 79:9; 109:21).</p>',
    "5": '<p>"But I have trusted in your steadfast love (<em>ḥeseḏ</em>)" — the pivot from lament to trust. <em>Ḥeseḏ</em> is covenantal loyalty: God\'s faithful adherence to his covenant commitments, not transient emotion. The psalmist\'s trust is not in a feeling but in a covenant attribute. "My heart will rejoice in your salvation (<em>yĕšûʿātĕkā</em>)" — the prospective perfect: the psalmist speaks of not-yet-experienced salvation as already certain because God\'s <em>ḥeseḏ</em> guarantees it. This grammar of faith (speaking future salvation as present reality) is the Psalter\'s characteristic mode of trust.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"I will sing to the LORD, for he has been generous (<em>gāmal ʿālay</em>) to me" — the sudden resolution. No explanation is given for the transition from distress (v. 4) to praise (v. 6): the psalmist simply arrives there. This unnarrated pivot is characteristic of the individual lament form. Scholars have proposed various explanations: an intervening priestly oracle now absent from the text, the act of prayer itself as transformative, or the conscious choice of trust as an act of will. In any case, the worshipping community would recognize this pattern from repeated liturgical experience of moving through lament into praise.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 14 is nearly identical to Psalm 53, with systematic substitution of <em>YHWH</em> for <em>Elohim</em> — the same poem appears twice in the Psalter in two different theological collections (Pss 3-41 use YHWH; Pss 42-83 prefer Elohim). The <em>nābāl</em> (fool) who says "there is no God" is not a philosophical atheist but a moral-practical one — <em>nābāl</em> derives from a root meaning "to wither/fade" (the same root as Nabal in 1 Sam 25, whose name his wife acknowledges means "fool"). The denial is not of God\'s existence but of his moral governance: the practical posture that divine accountability does not extend to one\'s actions.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"The LORD looks down from heaven on all people to see if there are any who understand (<em>maśkîl</em>), who seek God (<em>dōrēš ʾĕlōhîm</em>)" — the divine survey from heaven parallels Gen 11:5 (Tower of Babel — "the LORD came down to see") and Gen 18:21 (Sodom). God\'s "looking down" is a forensic examination. <em>Maśkîl</em> (one who understands/acts with wisdom) and <em>dōrēš ʾĕlōhîm</em> (seeking God) are parallel: to seek God is the definition of wisdom. This reverses the common modern assumption that intellectual sophistication dismisses religious inquiry.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"All have turned aside; all have become corrupt together; there is no one who does good, not even one" — the universal indictment. Paul quotes this verse along with Pss 5:9; 10:7; 36:1; 140:3; Isa 59:7-8; and Prov 1:16 in Romans 3:10-18 to establish universal human sinfulness as the theological basis for universal need of the gospel. In the psalm\'s original context, "all" likely refers to the generation of the godless described in vv. 1-4 — but Paul draws out the text\'s full anthropological scope, reading the Hebrew totality language as a genuine universal claim.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Those who devour my people as they eat bread" — the devouring of "my people" (<em>ʿammî</em>) is striking language: the wicked treat Israel\'s vulnerable community as food, consumed casually and without hesitation. "And who do not call on the LORD" — in ancient Israel, meals were covenant occasions as well as sustenance; to eat without calling on YHWH was to deny the covenant context of all provision. The "workers of evil" (<em>pōʿălê ʾāwen</em>) are defined by their total mode of action — <em>ʾāwen</em> combining wickedness, idolatry, and futility.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"There they were filled with fear, for God is with the righteous generation (<em>dôr ṣaddîq</em>)" — "there" (<em>šām</em>) is the place where the wicked enact their oppression. The sudden terror overtakes them when they encounter God\'s presence with the righteous community — the divine solidarity the wicked\'s theology had denied. "The righteous generation" is the covenant community defined not by birth but by moral-covenantal alignment: those who seek God (v. 2). Their presence (or God\'s with them) constitutes the shock that breaks the wicked\'s assumed impunity.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"You would shame the plans of the poor (<em>bôšîšû ʿăṣat-ʿānî</em>)" — the psalmist addresses the wicked directly. Their strategy of shaming the poor — stripping them of social honor and undermining their strategies — fails because YHWH himself is the poor\'s <em>maḥseh</em> (shelter, refuge). The honor-shame mechanism the wicked deploys against the poor is overridden by divine advocacy: the ultimate patron of the patron-less is YHWH, whose honor-claim on behalf of the poor cannot be overridden by any human court or social power.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Oh, that salvation for Israel would come from Zion!" — the eschatological longing. Zion as the source of salvation draws on the Zion theology in which YHWH\'s throne on Zion is the origin of divine action for his people. "When the LORD restores the fortunes of his people (<em>bĕšûb yhwh šĕbût ʿammô</em>)" — the idiom <em>šûb šĕbût</em> (restore fortunes, literally "turn the captivity") was associated in Second Temple Judaism with the return from Exile and, eschatologically, with the restoration of all things. The psalm ends facing the future, hoping for what is not yet fully present.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 15 is an entrance liturgy — a question-and-answer ritual performed at the gates of the sanctuary before entry. Psalm 24 has the same structure ("Who may ascend the hill of the LORD?"), and Isaiah 33:14-16 and Micah 6:6-8 show the same genre operating in prophetic contexts. Pilgrims approaching the sanctuary would ask "Who may dwell in your sanctuary?" and a priest or the congregation would answer with the ethical requirements. The two verbs — <em>gûr</em> (sojourn, temporary dwelling) and <em>šākan</em> (dwell, permanent residence) — together span both temporary access and full covenant belonging to the holy mountain.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"The one who walks blamelessly (<em>tāmîm</em>), does what is right (<em>ṣedeq</em>), and speaks truth from the heart" — three positive qualifications. <em>Tāmîm</em> (blameless, integrity of wholeness) is the term used of Noah (Gen 6:9) and Job (Job 1:1) — not sinless perfection but undivided moral integrity; the opposite of the divided heart in Ps 12:2. "Does what is right" is covenant-justice in practice. "Speaks truth from the heart" — heart and mouth aligned — is the antithesis of the duplicity condemned in Ps 12 and the flattery condemned throughout the Psalter.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Who does not slander with the tongue (<em>rāḡal ʿal-lĕšônô</em>)" — literally "foot it on his tongue," the idiom for one who goes about from house to house bearing tales (cf. Lev 19:16 — "do not go about spreading slander"). Social harm (<em>rāʿāh</em>) to a neighbor and reproach against a friend cover the range of speech that damages reputation. In ancient Israel, one\'s standing in the community was inseparable from one\'s social life — to damage reputation was to harm the person at the most fundamental level of their social existence.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Who despises the contemptible but honors those who fear the LORD; who keeps an oath even when it costs (<em>nišbaʿ lĕhāraʿ wĕlōʾ yāmîr</em>)" — to honor YHWH-fearers while despising the dishonorable inverts normal social dynamics where power and wealth determine honor. "Swears to his own hurt and does not change" — in ancient commercial and social life, oaths were legally and spiritually binding; to renege on a sworn commitment was both social treachery and covenant violation. The one who keeps costly oaths demonstrates that their word is genuinely reliable, not self-serving.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Who does not lend money at interest (<em>nešek</em>) or take a bribe (<em>šōḥad</em>) against the innocent" — the Torah prohibited lending at interest to fellow Israelites (Exod 22:25; Lev 25:35-37; Deut 23:19-20) though permitted it with foreigners. Interest-bearing loans were a primary mechanism of predatory wealth accumulation in the ancient economy: the small farmer who borrowed after a crop failure could lose his land within a season (cf. Neh 5:1-5). The bribe against the innocent was the standard form of judicial corruption that perverted the court system for the wealthy (Exod 23:8; Deut 16:19; Amos 5:12). "Whoever does these things will never be moved (<em>lōʾ yimmôṭ lĕʿôlām</em>)" — covenant stability.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 16 carries the superscription <em>miktam</em> — an uncertain genre term appearing in Pss 16 and 56-60. Proposed meanings include a "golden poem" (<em>kātam</em> = gold) or a penitential form, but no consensus exists. The psalm is centrally important for early Christian theology: Peter cites vv. 8-11 at Pentecost (Acts 2:25-28) and Paul cites v. 10 at Pisidian Antioch (Acts 13:35), both applying "your Holy One will not see decay" to Jesus\'s resurrection. The opening "keep me safe (<em>šāmrēnî</em>) for in you I take shelter (<em>ḥāsîtî</em>)" establishes the covenantal posture of complete dependence — <em>ḥāsāh</em> (take refuge) is the root of <em>maḥseh</em> (refuge), the Psalter\'s standard term for divine protection.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"I said to the LORD, \'You are my Lord (<em>ʾādonāy</em>); I have no good apart from you.\'" — the radical covenant confession: God is the source of all good, not only religious or spiritual good. <em>ʾĀdonāy</em> (my Lord) is the respectful vocative form used for YHWH. "My good is nothing without you (<em>ṭôbātî bal-ʿāleykā</em>)" is textually and grammatically debated (the LXX reads it differently), but in context expresses absolute dependence: all benefit flows from the relationship with YHWH; outside it there is no <em>ṭôb</em> (good, flourishing).</p>',
    "3": '<p>"As for the holy ones who are in the land, they are the noble — in them is all my delight" — this verse is textually difficult. The most natural reading: the <em>qĕdôšîm</em> (holy ones) are the covenant faithful in Israel, the pious community. Their nobility (<em>ʾaddîrê</em>) is not social rank but spiritual standing. The psalmist\'s delight (<em>ḥēpeṣ</em>) in the community of the faithful mirrors YHWH\'s own delight in the righteous (Ps 147:11) — the psalmist\'s values align with God\'s, forming a coherent pattern of covenant loyalty at both the vertical and horizontal dimensions.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"The sorrows of those who chase other gods will multiply" — the covenant warning of Deut 28-30: apostasy produces suffering. <em>ʿAṣbôtām</em> (sorrows, idols — the same root as <em>ʿōṣeḇ</em>, idol) may be a deliberate wordplay: both their idols and their sorrows will multiply. "I will not pour out their libations of blood" — blood libations were Canaanite or foreign ritual practices; Israelite law strictly prohibited the drinking of blood (Lev 17:10-14) and blood-ritual worship. The psalmist refuses cultic assimilation to surrounding practices, maintaining covenant distinctiveness.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"The LORD is my allotted portion (<em>mĕnāt-ḥelqî</em>) and my cup (<em>kôsî</em>)" — two layered images. (1) <em>Ḥēleq</em> (portion, allotment): the Levites received no tribal land inheritance because YHWH was their portion (Num 18:20; Deut 10:9; 18:2) — to be sustained by the altar, not the earth. The psalmist claims the same priestly relationship: not land but YHWH himself is the inheritance. (2) The cup: in covenant ritual, the cup of blessing was passed at sacred meals (cf. 1 Cor 10:16); the cup could also contain wrath (Ps 11:6; 75:8; Isa 51:17). Here the cup is blessing.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"The boundary lines have fallen for me in pleasant places; truly I have a beautiful inheritance" — land allotment language. When Joshua divided Canaan by lot, each tribe received its <em>ḥēleq</em> (inheritance), the boundary lines (<em>ḥăbālîm</em>) marking the permanent grant (Josh 18-19). The psalmist applies this to his relationship with God: the "inheritance" of divine fellowship is more desirable than any parcel of land. The contentment expressed — "pleasant places (<em>nĕʿîmôt</em>)," "beautiful inheritance (<em>šāpĕrāh ʿālay</em>)" — echoes the šālôm of Ps 4:7-8: satisfaction from the divine presence itself rather than material provision.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"I will praise the LORD who counsels me (<em>yĕʿāṣênî</em>); even at night my inmost self (<em>kĕlāyôtay</em> — kidneys) instructs me" — divine counsel received in the night connects Ps 16 with Ps 17 (also a night vigil). The kidneys (<em>kĕlāyôt</em>) were the seat of deep feeling and moral discernment in ancient Israelite anthropology (cf. Jer 11:20; 17:10; 20:12 — where God examines the kidneys and heart), analogous to the modern conscience or deepest intuition. Divine instruction reaches the deepest level of the person, not merely the conscious surface.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"I have set the LORD always before me; because he is at my right hand (<em>liymînî</em>), I will not be shaken" — the right hand is the position of the chief advocate, counselor, or protector (cf. Ps 110:1 — God says to the Davidic lord: "sit at my right hand"). The king\'s military commander stood at his right hand. Peter at Pentecost (Acts 2:25) quotes this verse and the following as David speaking prophetically of Christ — the one who is now literally exalted to God\'s right hand (Acts 2:33). The covenant-stability phrase "will not be shaken" recurs across Pss 10-21.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"My heart is glad and my spirit (<em>kābôd</em>, lit. glory/honor-self) rejoices; my body (<em>bāśār</em>, flesh) also rests secure" — the triad of heart (<em>lēb</em>), glory-self (<em>kābôd</em>), and body (<em>bāśār</em>) expresses total well-being. Using <em>kābôd</em> for the inner self is unusual — possibly the psalmist\'s social-spiritual honor-identity. The LXX translates <em>kābôd</em> as <em>glōssa</em> (tongue), a significant deviation that shapes Peter\'s quotation in Acts 2:26 ("therefore my heart was glad, and my tongue rejoiced"). The Hebrew triad and the LXX triad each emphasize totality of wellbeing.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"For you will not leave my soul (<em>nafšî</em>) in Sheol, or let your Holy One (<em>ḥăsîdĕkā</em>) see decay (<em>šaḥat</em>)" — the center of the NT\'s reading of Ps 16. Peter (Acts 2:27-31) and Paul (Acts 13:35-37) argue that David cannot be speaking only of himself, since David did die and his tomb was known in Jerusalem; therefore, David spoke prophetically of Christ\'s resurrection as the fulfillment of the non-decaying Holy One. <em>Šaḥat</em> (pit/decay) — whether it means the pit of Sheol or physical decomposition carries significant interpretive weight. The psalm originally expresses personal confidence in divine preservation from death; the NT reads the promise as pointing beyond any Davidic fulfillment.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"You will make known to me the path of life (<em>ʾōraḥ ḥayyîm</em>); in your presence is complete joy (<em>śimbat pānîm</em>); at your right hand are pleasures forevermore (<em>nĕʿimôt niṣṣaḥ</em>)" — <em>Ōraḥ ḥayyîm</em> (path of life) is wisdom language: the way that leads away from death (Prov 2:19; 5:6; 10:17). The complete joy in God\'s presence contrasts with the multiplied sorrows of those who chase other gods (v. 4). "Pleasures forevermore" is an eschatological horizon — joy in God\'s presence has no terminus. The psalm closes not at Sheol but at the right hand of God, where the fullness of joy and eternal pleasures reside.</p>'
  },
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>Psalm 17 is a royal prayer — the king petitions for divine vindication against unjust enemies, and the language is consistently forensic throughout. "Hear a just cause (<em>ṣedeq</em>), O LORD; listen to my cry; give ear to my prayer from lips without deceit (<em>mirmāh</em>)" — the king approaches God as a plaintiff before the divine court, claiming the justice of his cause and the sincerity of his petition. "Lips without deceit" is the claim of complete rhetorical integrity — no manipulation, no flattery, no hidden agenda (contrasting with Ps 12:2-4\'s corrupt speech). The divine court is the final court of appeal when human courts fail.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"Let my vindication (<em>mišpāṭî</em>) come from you; let your eyes behold what is just (<em>mêšārîm</em>)" — <em>mišpāṭ</em> is both legal process and verdict: the psalmist requests that the divine judge render a fair decision. "Behold what is just" — the impartial divine gaze (cf. Ps 9:8; 11:4) is exactly what the psalmist invites. The petition is not for special favor but for honest judgment, confident that honest judgment will vindicate. This is the radical confidence of Ps 1\'s theology: the righteous need only ask for divine scrutiny, not divine partiality.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"You have tested my heart; you have examined me through the night; you have tried me (<em>ṣĕraftanî</em>) and found nothing" — the refining metaphor again (cf. Ps 12:6). <em>Ṣāraf</em> is the metallurgist\'s verb: to smelt, assay, refine metal in fire. God has applied the refiner\'s examination and found no impurity. "Through the night" — either the night of a temple vigil during which this prayer was offered (a common practice; cf. Ps 16:7 and 17:15), or the ongoing night of trial and suffering through which God has been silently watching and testing the psalmist\'s integrity.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"By the word of your lips I have avoided the ways of the violent (<em>pārîṣ</em>)" — the claim of Torah-shaped formation. "By the word of your lips (<em>biḏbar śĕpātêkā</em>)" — the psalmist has shaped his conduct by divine speech, not by cultural convention. <em>Pārîṣ</em> (violent, destructive) describes the social predator of Pss 10, 12, 14. The word of God functions as counter-formation, creating a person whose character resists the ambient culture of violence — an ethic shaped from above, not from below.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"My steps have kept to your paths (<em>ʾăšûrōtay</em>); my feet have not stumbled (<em>lōʾ-māṭû</em>)" — <em>ʾāšar</em> (to step, go straight) and <em>nāṭāh</em> (to turn aside, deviate) form the contrast. The paths of God are the covenant way of Torah; stumbling is the standard metaphor for moral failure in wisdom literature (Prov 3:23; 4:12; Isa 59:10). The path metaphor in the Psalms (Pss 1, 23, 25, 27) reflects the ancient understanding of covenant life as a journey on a defined road — not a series of isolated ethical decisions but a sustained directional movement.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"I call on you, for you will answer me, O God; turn your ear (<em>haṭṭēh-ʾoznĕkā</em>) to me; hear my words" — the confidence of petition grounded in covenant relationship. "Turn your ear" is a physical idiom: the judge or patron physically turning to give ear signals willingness to receive a petition. In ancient Mediterranean patronage, the ability to get access to a powerful person\'s ear was the key social currency. The psalmist claims access to the greatest patron — not by social standing but by covenant — with the confidence that YHWH will incline toward those who call on him.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Display your wonderful steadfast love (<em>hapleʾ ḥăsādêkā</em>), O Savior (<em>môšîaʿ</em>) of those who seek refuge from their enemies by your right hand" — <em>Hapleʾ</em> (make wonderful, distinguish, make visible) — make the <em>ḥeseḏ</em> conspicuously evident. <em>Môšîaʿ</em> is the Hiphil participle of <em>yāšaʿ</em> (save): the one who saves, the deliverer. This is the root of <em>yēšûaʿ</em> (Joshua/Jesus) — "the LORD saves." The petition invokes God\'s covenant name and saving character simultaneously, asking for a visible demonstration of <em>ḥeseḏ</em> against the background of military threat.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Guard me as the apple of your eye (<em>ʾîšôn bat-ʿāyin</em>); hide me in the shadow of your wings" — two protection images. (1) <em>ʾIšôn</em> (apple of the eye) literally means "little man" — the tiny image one sees reflected in another\'s pupil; by extension, what is most precious and most carefully guarded. Cf. Deut 32:10 — God keeps Israel "as the apple of his eye." (2) Shadow of wings (<em>bĕṣēl kĕnāpêkā</em>) — God protecting as a bird covers its young (Deut 32:11; Ruth 2:12; Pss 36:7; 57:1; 61:4; 91:4). Both images express the intimate, attentive protection of what is most valued.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"From the wicked who assail me, from my deadly enemies (<em>ʾōyĕbay bĕnepeš</em> — enemies against the soul/life) who encircle me" — the military encirclement image. In ancient siege warfare, to encircle a city cut off escape and supply — the total vulnerability of the besieged. The phrase "enemies against the soul/life" specifies those who seek not mere defeat but complete annihilation — <em>nepeš</em> (life, soul, the person) itself is what they target. The psalmist is not dealing with political opposition but with enemies who want him utterly destroyed.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Their hearts are closed to compassion (<em>ḥelbāmô sāgerû</em> — their fat encloses them); their mouths speak with arrogance" — "their fat" (<em>ḥēleb</em>) refers to the rich fat around vital organs. To be enclosed in fat is to be insulated against any perception of others\' suffering — self-satisfied, impervious. This physiological metaphor for moral imperviousness recurs in the Prophets: Isaiah 6:10 (heart fat, ears heavy, eyes closed); Jeremiah 5:28 (the wicked grow fat and sleek). The sequence is anatomically precise: a fat heart produces an arrogant mouth.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Now they surround our every step; they watch for a chance to bring us to the ground (<em>lintôt bāʾāreṣ</em> — to stretch us out on the earth)" — the shift from "me" (my steps, my feet — vv. 5, 11) to "us" (bring us to the ground) suggests the prayer has a communal dimension: the king petitions for himself and his community together. The watching for a moment of vulnerability (<em>ʿênêhem yāšîtû</em> — their eyes they set) is the predatory gaze scanning for the opportune moment, the same gaze as the lion crouching in Ps 10:9-10.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"He is like a lion (<em>ʾaryēh</em>) eager for prey, like a young lion (<em>kĕpîr</em>) crouching in ambush" — the dual lion image, recalling Ps 10:9. <em>ʾAryēh</em> (mature lion) and <em>kĕpîr</em> (young male lion in his prime — the most dangerous) emphasize both power and cunning at their peak. ANE royal iconography regularly depicted enemies as lions to be defeated — the king\'s prowess was demonstrated by subduing both wild animals and foreign enemies. David\'s lion-killing (1 Sam 17:34-37) established his credentials as the one capable of overcoming such threats; here the enemy takes the lion\'s role against the psalmist.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Arise, LORD! Confront him! Bring him down! Rescue me from the wicked by your sword" — five imperatives in rapid succession. The battle-cry <em>qûmāh yhwh</em> (Arise, LORD) echoes Num 10:35 (the ark\'s departure formula), Pss 3:7; 7:6; 9:19; 10:12. The urgency and compression of five consecutive imperatives mirrors the panic of immediate threat. "Your sword (<em>ḥarbĕkā</em>)" — God as divine warrior brandishing his weapon is widespread in ANE iconography and biblical tradition: Deut 32:41-43 ("I will sharpen my flashing sword"); Isa 66:16; Ezek 21.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"By your hand, LORD, from those whose portion (<em>ḥeleq</em>) is in this present life" — the enemies are "men whose portion is in this life" — contrasting sharply with Ps 16:5 (YHWH as the psalmist\'s portion). The wicked have no heavenly inheritance; this world\'s goods are their entire allotment. "Their belly is filled with what you store up" — God is giving them temporal prosperity (their "portion"), yet this is precisely what makes them dangerous. Their children will inherit what remains, but the inheritance is finite. The contrast with the psalmist\'s eternal inheritance (Ps 16:11) frames the psalm\'s two competing life-orientations.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"As for me, I will behold your face in righteousness (<em>ṣedeq</em>); when I awake I will be satisfied with your likeness (<em>tĕmûnātĕkā</em>)" — the closing verse sets the ultimate contrast with v. 14. The wicked have their entire portion in this life; the psalmist\'s portion is the vision of God. "Beholding the face" is the language of temple access — to see God\'s face in the sanctuary (Pss 11:7; 42:2; 63:2). <em>Tĕmûnāh</em> (likeness, form) suggests a vision of divine glory — the manifestation of God\'s presence, not direct access to the divine essence (cf. Num 12:8, where Moses sees the <em>tĕmûnāh</em> of YHWH). "When I awake" carries both the immediate sense of dawn after a night vigil and an eschatological overtone resonating with Ps 16:10\'s resurrection hope.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms')
    merge_comm(existing, PSALMS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'psalms', existing)
    print('Psalms 9–17 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
